results.name: Number of rings with 1 containing n elements.
comment: Many authors simply call these "rings". They are also known as unital rings, rings with unity, or rings with identity. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 12 2015

Is this sequence multiplicative? That is, if p and q are distinct primes, is it true that a(p^i*q^j) = a(p^i)*a(q^j)? - _Jianing Song_, Oct 26 2019. The answer is yes - see the Eric M. Rains link. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Oct 27 2019
link: C. Noebauer, Home page [Archived copy as of 2008 from web.archive.org]
Eric M. Rains, The number of unital rings with n elements is a multiplicative function of n.
